  "htmlText": "<h3>Web worker demo (uses libraries/web_worker_demo.js file)</h3>\nWeb workers allow you to run processor intensive activity on a background thread.  The Web Worker API was \ncreated by W3C so it should in theory be supported across many browsers.  Internet explorer added support \nfor web workers in IE10 and i believe it supports up to 25 simulateneous web workers (according to their page \n<a class=\"TridentLinkSmall\" href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ie/hh673568(v=vs.85).aspx\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>).  \n<br/><br/>\nThis example taken from : <a class=\"TridentLinkSmall\" href=\"http://www.w3schools.com/html/html5_webworkers.asp\" target=\"_blank\">W3Schools</a><br/>\n<p>Count numbers: <output id=\"result\"></output></p>\n<button onclick=\"startWorker()\">Start Worker</button> \n<button onclick=\"stopWorker()\">Stop Worker</button>\n<br><br>",
  "scriptText": "var sandboxVars = {\n    w: null\n};\n\nsandbox.events.clean = function () {\n    if (sandboxVars.w) {\n        sandboxVars.w.terminate();\n        delete sandboxVars.w;\n    }\n};\n\nfunction startWorker()\n{\n    if(typeof(Worker) !== \"undefined\")\n    {\n        if(sandboxVars.w == null)\n        {\n            sandboxVars.w = new Worker(\"libraries/web_worker_demo.js\");\n        }\n        sandboxVars.w.onmessage = function (event){\n            document.getElementById(\"result\").innerHTML = event.data;\n        };\n    }\n    else\n    {\n        document.getElementById(\"result\").innerHTML=\"Sorry, your browser does not support Web Workers...\";\n    }\n}\n\nfunction stopWorker()\n{ \n    sandboxVars.w.terminate();\n    sandboxVars.w = null;\n}"
